@node "Output" "Output"

  @{b}@{u}Output@{ub}@{uu}

  When PPMS is compiling or building a project it will tell you what is
  going on and why. When a file is compiled because it's source is newer
  than it's object it will say so, also if the source is compiled because
  a dependant file is newer than the object file it will tell you which
  dependant file caused the compilation. The same applies for checking
  includes - it will tell you which include file caused the re-compilation.

  The only input the output window allows is CONTROL-C and CONTROL-F.
  CONTROL-C will break compilation or linking and terminate unless:
  CONTROL-F is pressed first which instructs PPMS to just 'skip' this file.

  So if you are building a project and want to terminate immediately just
  press CONTROL-C. But if you are building a project and want to skip one
  file only (for example you are done an optimized build of all files and
  the file PPMS is up to is going to be altered in a moment by you) then
  you press CONTROL-F then CONTROL-C and PPMS will only skip that file and
  continue to build all the other files. (then you have all the files
  optimized except the one you want to alter; and you can alter it and just
  do a plain build which will complete the optimized build).     
@endnode

@node "Loading" "Loading"

  @{b}@{u}Loading PPMS@{ub}@{uu}

  You can load PPMS in one of the following ways:

   - By double clicking on the PPMS icon.
     PPMS supports the following ToolTypes:
       PROJECT=<filename> - Will load the project <filename>
       SHOW               - Will open the main window

   - By CLI with the template "PROJECT,SHOW/S"

   - By double clicking on one of it's project icons.
     If the project has a default editor then PPMS will attempt to
     find the editor's AREXX port. If the editor's arexx port is
     not present PPMS will attempt to start the editor.      
@endnode

